Covalent Bonding

01 Chlorine atoms: each shares 1 electron → single covalent bond (Cl₂) 02 Electrostatic attraction in a covalent bond 03 CO₂ dot & cross diagram (double bonds) 04 Ethene (C₂H₄) dot & cross with a C=C double bond 05 Covalent bonds are strong; intermolecular forces are weak 06 C₆₀ fullerene (buckyball) structure 07 Boiling point increases with molecular mass (alkanes) 08 Diamond: each carbon forms four bonds (giant covalent) 09 Graphite: layered structure with weak forces between planes

Mind Map

Flow: Formation → Dot & Cross → Simple Molecules → Boiling Point & Conductivity → Giant Covalent → Diamond & Graphite.

01 • Formation of Covalent Bonds

  • Non-metal atoms share electrons to get a full outer shell.
  • Each shared pair = a covalent bond; bonds are very strong.
  • Substances may be simple molecular or giant covalent.

02 • Dot & Cross Diagrams

03 • Simple Molecular Structures

  • Strong bonds within molecules; weak intermolecular forces between molecules.
  • Therefore low melting & boiling points; many are gases/liquids.
  • Larger molecules → stronger intermolecular forces → higher b.p.

04 • C60 Fullerene

  • Carbon allotrope: hollow sphere with interlocking pentagons & hexagons.
  • Uses: trapping molecules, catalyst support, lubricants.
  • Simple molecular; weak forces between buckyballs; poor conductor.

05 • Melting/Boiling Trends

  • As relative molecular mass increases, boiling point increases.
  • Reason: more electrons → stronger temporary attractions → more energy to separate molecules.

06 • Conductivity

  • Simple molecular substances are poor conductors (no free ions/electrons).
Low b.p. because intermolecular forces are weak.
They conduct when molten due to delocalised electrons.
Melting breaks covalent bonds inside molecules.

07 • Giant Covalent Structures

  • Huge networks of atoms; very high melting points.
  • Examples: diamond, graphite.

08 • Diamond

  • Each C bonded to four others (tetrahedral); extremely hard.
  • High m.p. because many strong covalent bonds must be broken.

09 • Graphite

  • Each C bonded to three others → layers that slide (weak forces between planes).
  • Conducts electricity due to delocalised electrons.
